The new R-matrix analysis of the N-N system on which the ENDF/B-   125 1451
VII evaluation for 1H is based differs from the previous one use   125 1451
for ENDF/B-VI in several respects. Firstly, the n-p capture        125 1451
reaction (MT=102), and its inverse, deuteron photo-                125 1451
disintegration, were a part of the analysis, rather than added     125 1451
later as before. The analysis used a new method for including      125 1451
photon channels in R-matrix theory [1], which gave a better        125 1451
description of the E1 transitions, in particular.  The data for    125 1451
these reactions are mostly integrated and differential cross       125 1451
sections, but some information about polarizations was also        125 1451
included.  The thermal capture cross section was taken to be       125 1451
332.0 mb, as was the recommendation from preliminary data          125 1451
testing. Good agreement was obtained with recent cross-section     125 1451
measurements [2,3] by astrophysical groups in the 20-550 keV       125 1451
range, as well as with earlier measurements that had been done     125 1451
mostly as photo-disintegration experiments at energies below 14    125 1451
MeV.                                                               125 1451
The new analysis includes several additional measurements of the   125 1451
total cross section (MT=1).  The evaluated cross section           125 1451
deviates at most by about -0.5% around 10 MeV from that of         125 1451
ENDF/B-VI.  The estimated uncertainty of the MT=1 cross section    125 1451
is given at 2 MeV steps in the following table:                    125 1451
           En             Uncert. (%)                              125 1451
            0                0.20                                  125 1451
            2                0.22                                  125 1451
            4                0.30                                  125 1451
            6                0.36                                  125 1451
            8                0.44                                  125 1451
           10                0.50                                  125 1451
           12                0.49                                  125 1451
           14                0.46                                  125 1451
           16                0.40                                  125 1451
           18                0.35                                  125 1451
           20                0.30                                  125 1451
                                                                   125 1451
For n-p scattering (MT=2), new information was included about the  125 1451
low-energy cross sections (MF=3) and about the angular             125 1451
distributions (MF=4).  A new measurement of the angular            125 1451
distribution at 10 MeV [4], plus corrections to earlier data at    125 1451
14 MeV, moved the back-angle asymmetry in the 10-14 MeV range to   125 1451
values that lie between those obtained for ENDF/B-V and ENDF/B-    125 1451
VI.  The addition of the latest value of the thermal coherent      125 1451
scattering length [5] had the interesting effect of reducing the   125 1451
"zero-energy" scattering cross section somewhat to agree           125 1451
perfectly with an earlier measurement by Houk [6], and disagree    125 1451
with the later, more precise, value of Dilg [7].  The              125 1451
covariances for MT=2 will be added later, but the uncertainties    125 1451
on the integrated cross section should be similar to those         125 1451
listed above for the total cross section.                          125 1451
